data.alert_description: On {{trigger_date}}, Deepwatch detected potential C2 multi-stage behavior at {{src}}. {{signature_count}} distinct admin events occurred within a 15 minute timeframe of communications with remote destination(s): {{signature}}.
data.alert_drilldown: `dwa_windows_indices` `dwa_windows_sec_sourcetype` (signature_id=5156 `dwa_enda_00086_address_range`) OR (signature_id IN (4664,4720,4722,4724,4728,4738,4765,4766,4782,4797,4946,4947,4948,4949,4950,4781,4756,5376,5377,4698,4700,4727,4754,4780,4798,4706)) `dwa_enda_00086_initial_exceptions` dest="{{src}}" | `dwa_windows_coalesce` | rename dest as src | `dwa_rule_exclusions(dwa_enda_00086,signature_id)` | `dwa_rule_exclusions(dwa_enda_00086,DestAddress)` | `dwa_rule_exclusions(dwa_enda_00086,Application)` | rex field=Message "(?<signature_ext>.+\.)" | eval signature=coalesce(signature,signature_ext) | eval signature=if(isnull(signature), case(signature_id=="4797", "An attempt was made to query the existence of a blank password for an account", signature_id=="4798", "A user's local group membership was enumerated.", signature_id=="4765", "SID History was added to an account."), signature) | fillnull Application value="unknown" | eval signature_id=if(signature_id=="5156", signature_id.": ".Application, signature_id) | eventstats values(DestPort) as DestPort values(DestAddress) as Dest_Address by Application | dedup signature_id | table _time index sourcetype src signature_id signature app DestAddress DestPort | sort -_time
data.alert_title: Potential C2 multi-stage behavior at {{src}}: {{signature_count}} distinct admin events
data.signature: 4724: An attempt was made to reset an accounts password, 4738: A user account was changed, 4781: The name of an account was changed, 5156: The Windows Filtering Platform has allowed a connection
data.splunk_spl:
`dwa_windows_indices` `dwa_windows_sec_sourcetype` (signature_id=5156 `dwa_enda_00086_address_range`) OR (signature_id IN (4664,4720,4722,4724,4728,4738,4765,4766,4782,4797,4946,4947,4948,4949,4950,4781,4756,5376,5377,4698,4700,4727,4754,4780,4798,4706)) `dwa_enda_00086_initial_exceptions` 
| `dwa_windows_coalesce` 
| rename dest as src 
| `dwa_rule_exclusions(dwa_enda_00086,signature_id)` 
| `dwa_rule_exclusions(dwa_enda_00086,src)` 
| `dwa_rule_exclusions(dwa_enda_00086,DestAddress)` 
| `dwa_rule_exclusions(dwa_enda_00086,Application)` 
| rex field=Message "(?<signature_ext>.+\.)" 
| eval signature=coalesce(signature,signature_ext) 
| eval signature=if(isnull(signature), case(signature_id=="4797", "An attempt was made to query the existence of a blank password for an account", signature_id=="4798", "A user's local group membership was enumerated.", signature_id=="4765", "SID History was added to an account."), signature) 
| eval signature=signature_id.": ".signature 
| stats latest(_time) as _time dc(DestAddress) as DestAddress_count values(DestAddress) as DestAddress dc(Application) as app_count values(Application) as app values(signature) as signature values(signature_id) as signature_id dc(signature_id) as signature_count by src index sourcetype 
| `dwa_watchlist(dwa_enda_00086, app)`
| where (match(signature_id,"5156") AND isnotnull(DestAddress) AND signature_count > `dwa_enda_00086_threshold`) OR (match(signature_id,"5156") AND match(watchlist_type,"SuspiciousWFPConnection")) 
| `dwa_limit_multivalues(DestAddress,DestAddress_count)` 
| `dwa_limit_multivalues(app,app_count)` 
| `dwa_limit_multivalues(signature,signature_count)` 
| eval signature_count=signature_count - 1 
| `dwa_enda_00086_exceptions` 
| dedup src 
| table _time index sourcetype src signature_count signature_id signature watchlist_comment app_count app DestAddress_count DestAddress 
| `dwa_risk(dwa_enda_00086,,src)` 
| `dwa_metadata(dwa_enda_00086)`

policy_details.alert_logic:
1. Generate List of MFA Devices, matching on 'root'.|
2. Alert if MFA Device is null.
policy_details.cli_command: aws2 iam list-users, aws2 iam list-mfa-devices
policy_details.description: A hardware MFA has a smaller attack surface than a virtual MFA. For example, a hardware MFA does not suffer the attack surface introduced by the mobile smartphone on which a virtual MFA resides.
policy_details.policy_remediation:
Step 1. Log into the AWS account using Root credentials.|
Step 2. In the navigation bar on the upper right, choose Security credentials.|
Step 3. Choose the "Security credentials" tab. Next to "Assigned MFA device", choose "Manage".|
Step 4. In the "Manage MFA" device wizard, choose "Remove", and then choose "Remove".|
Step 5. On the AWS IAM credentials tab, in the Multi-factor authentication section, choose Manage MFA device.|
Step 6. Determine if using FIDO key or TOTP token.|
Step 7. (If using FIDO key) In the "Manage MFA" device wizard, choose "FIDO security key", and then choose "Continue".|
Step 8. Insert the FIDO security key into your computer's USB port.|
Step 9. Tap the FIDO security key, and then choose Close when setup is complete.|
Step 10. (If using a hardware TOTP token) In the wizard, choose "Hardware TOTP token" and then choose "Continue".|
Step 11. In the "Serial number" box, type the serial number that is found on the back of the MFA device.|
Step 12. In the "MFA code 1" box, type the six-digit number displayed by the MFA device. You might need to press the button on the front of the device to display the number.|
Step 13. Wait 30 seconds while the device refreshes the code, and then type the next six-digit number into the "MFA code 2" box. You might need to press the button on the front of the device again to display the second number.|
Step 14. Choose "Assign MFA". The MFA device is now associated with the AWS account.
